{
    "publish_date": "2012-12-02T21:54:33.000Z", 
    "video_length": "PT6M44S", 
    "captions": [
        {
            "text": "JAMES GRIME: 0.", 
            "dur": "0.02", 
            "start": "2.02"
        }, 
        {
            "text": "That&#39;s our friend.", 
            "dur": "1.48", 
            "start": "2.04"
        }, 
        {
            "text": "Yes.", 
            "dur": "0.64", 
            "start": "3.52"
        }, 
        {
            "text": "To a mathematician\nthis is a number.", 
            "dur": "1.85", 
            "start": "4.16"
        }, 
        {
            "text": "But it wasn&#39;t always obvious.", 
            "dur": "2.39", 
            "start": "6.01"
        }, 
        {
            "text": "ROGER BOWLEY: Math existed to do\nfinancial transactions, to", 
            "dur": "3.32", 
            "start": "8.4"
        }, 
        {
            "text": "sell sheep, to buy copper\nthings, whatever.", 
            "dur": "3.86", 
            "start": "11.72"
        }, 
        {
            "text": "And you would use coins.", 
            "dur": "2.2", 
            "start": "15.58"
        }, 
        {
            "text": "And there would be values\nto the coins.", 
            "dur": "1.76", 
            "start": "17.78"
        }, 
        {
            "text": "So you would say this\ncosts 5 pounds 20", 
            "dur": "2.425", 
            "start": "19.54"
        }, 
        {
            "text": "shillings, or whatever.", 
            "dur": "2.055", 
            "start": "21.965"
        }, 
        {
            "text": "You don&#39;t do any trading\nwith the number 0.", 
            "dur": "2.42", 
            "start": "24.02"
        }, 
        {
            "text": "I&#39;ve got no sheep here.", 
            "dur": "1.46", 
            "start": "26.44"
        }, 
        {
            "text": "Oh, I&#39;m gonna buy no sheep,\nI&#39;ll give you no pounds.", 
            "dur": "2.93", 
            "start": "27.9"
        }, 
        {
            "text": "It doesn&#39;t make any sense.", 
            "dur": "2.42", 
            "start": "30.83"
        }, 
        {
            "text": "So there was no need\nfor shopkeepers to", 
            "dur": "2.95", 
            "start": "33.25"
        }, 
        {
            "text": "invent the number 0.", 
            "dur": "1.33", 
            "start": "36.2"
        }, 
        {
            "text": "JAMES GRIME: They had\nthe idea of 5 cows.", 
            "dur": "2.74", 
            "start": "40.44"
        }, 
        {
            "text": "But the idea of 5,\nnot so much.", 
            "dur": "3.58", 
            "start": "43.18"
        }, 
        {
            "text": "The idea of 5-ness they didn&#39;t\nquite understand.", 
            "dur": "3.09", 
            "start": "46.76"
        }, 
        {
            "text": "So a number like 0, which\nis the absence of--", 
            "dur": "3.55", 
            "start": "49.85"
        }, 
        {
            "text": "well, whatever, cows,\nwhatever it was--", 
            "dur": "3.03", 
            "start": "53.4"
        }, 
        {
            "text": "made no sense to them.", 
            "dur": "1.5", 
            "start": "56.43"
        }, 
        {
            "text": "I&#39;m going ask Brady\na question.", 
            "dur": "1.69", 
            "start": "57.93"
        }, 
        {
            "text": "See if I can catch him out.", 
            "dur": "2.04", 
            "start": "59.62"
        }, 
        {
            "text": "Brady, is 0 an even number?", 
            "dur": "2.14", 
            "start": "61.66"
        }, 
        {
            "text": "BRADY HARAN: I think\nthe answer is no.", 
            "dur": "1.42", 
            "start": "67.48"
        }, 
        {
            "text": "But it feels like it is\nbecause it is round.", 
            "dur": "3.57", 
            "start": "68.9"
        }, 
        {
            "text": "JAMES GRIME: So this\nis an interesting--", 
            "dur": "1.78", 
            "start": "72.47"
        }, 
        {
            "text": "OK, let me ask another\nquestion.", 
            "dur": "0.92", 
            "start": "74.25"
        }, 
        {
            "text": "Is 16 an even number?", 
            "dur": "1.65", 
            "start": "75.17"
        }, 
        {
            "text": "BRADY HARAN: Yes.", 
            "dur": "0.36", 
            "start": "76.82"
        }, 
        {
            "text": "JAMES GRIME: Yes.", 
            "dur": "0.5", 
            "start": "77.18"
        }, 
        {
            "text": "So people have studied this.", 
            "dur": "2.87", 
            "start": "77.68"
        }, 
        {
            "text": "People have a delayed\nreaction.", 
            "dur": "2.02", 
            "start": "80.55"
        }, 
        {
            "text": "People are not sure whether\n0 is an even number.", 
            "dur": "3", 
            "start": "82.57"
        }, 
        {
            "text": "Now I can tell you that 0,", 
            "dur": "1.62", 
            "start": "85.57"
        }, 
        {
            "text": "categorically, is an even number.", 
            "dur": "2.99", 
            "start": "87.19"
        }, 
        {
            "text": "It will follow every definition\nof an even number.", 
            "dur": "4.5", 
            "start": "90.18"
        }, 
        {
            "text": "ROGER BOWLEY: So there was an\nIndian called Brahmagupta who", 
            "dur": "4.42", 
            "start": "94.68"
        }, 
        {
            "text": "invented the idea of nothing not\nbeing nothing but existing", 
            "dur": "5.1", 
            "start": "99.1"
        }, 
        {
            "text": "as an abstract quantity\nin the mathematics.", 
            "dur": "2.34", 
            "start": "104.2"
        }, 
        {
            "text": "Well, then it goes\nto North Africa.", 
            "dur": "3.57", 
            "start": "106.54"
        }, 
        {
            "text": "And there&#39;s a guy called\nAl Qasimi.", 
            "dur": "3.07", 
            "start": "110.11"
        }, 
        {
            "text": "And he writes a book about the\nart of Hindu mathematics and", 
            "dur": "3.6", 
            "start": "113.18"
        }, 
        {
            "text": "reckoning by Hindu\nmathematics.", 
            "dur": "2.13", 
            "start": "116.78"
        }, 
        {
            "text": "And that spreads through North\nAfrica to Spain and so forth.", 
            "dur": "4.16", 
            "start": "118.91"
        }, 
        {
            "text": "And it becomes, they think,\nArabic numbers.", 
            "dur": "2.64", 
            "start": "123.07"
        }, 
        {
            "text": "So you have all the\nnumbers plus 0.", 
            "dur": "4.079", 
            "start": "125.71"
        }, 
        {
            "text": "That was fine.", 
            "dur": "1", 
            "start": "129.789"
        }, 
        {
            "text": "Until 1200 when Leonardo of\nPisa, also known as Fibonacci,", 
            "dur": "5.811", 
            "start": "130.789"
        }, 
        {
            "text": "translates this book.", 
            "dur": "1.95", 
            "start": "136.6"
        }, 
        {
            "text": "It&#39;s a wonderful idea.", 
            "dur": "1.8", 
            "start": "138.55"
        }, 
        {
            "text": "But this is in the period\nof the Crusades.", 
            "dur": "3.2", 
            "start": "140.35"
        }, 
        {
            "text": "So people think these are Arabic\nnumbers, not Hindu", 
            "dur": "2.78", 
            "start": "143.55"
        }, 
        {
            "text": "numbers because it&#39;s come\nfrom North Africa.", 
            "dur": "3.47", 
            "start": "146.33"
        }, 
        {
            "text": "So the Catholic church objects\nto this because there are", 
            "dur": "5.4", 
            "start": "149.8"
        }, 
        {
            "text": "Crusades going on and this\nis the work of the enemy.", 
            "dur": "2.61", 
            "start": "155.2"
        }, 
        {
            "text": "So in Florence, for example,\nthey banned the use of this", 
            "dur": "3.35", 
            "start": "157.81"
        }, 
        {
            "text": "Arabic number 0.", 
            "dur": "1.91", 
            "start": "161.16"
        }, 
        {
            "text": "And it was thought to be\nthe work of the devil.", 
            "dur": "2.65", 
            "start": "163.07"
        }, 
        {
            "text": "BRADY HARAN: Because my\ndefinition of an even number", 
            "dur": "1.6", 
            "start": "165.72"
        }, 
        {
            "text": "is something that can\nbe divided by 2.", 
            "dur": "2.48", 
            "start": "167.32"
        }, 
        {
            "text": "JAMES GRIME: So Brady&#39;s just\ntold me an even number is a", 
            "dur": "4.05", 
            "start": "169.8"
        }, 
        {
            "text": "number that can be\ndivided by 2.", 
            "dur": "1.42", 
            "start": "173.85"
        }, 
        {
            "text": "Well, 0 can be divided by 2.", 
            "dur": "2.71", 
            "start": "175.27"
        }, 
        {
            "text": "0 divided by 2 is 0.", 
            "dur": "2.69", 
            "start": "177.98"
        }, 
        {
            "text": "In fact, in that sense, it\nis the most even number.", 
            "dur": "4.27", 
            "start": "180.67"
        }, 
        {
            "text": "In ancient times they had this\nidea of things being singly", 
            "dur": "3.09", 
            "start": "184.94"
        }, 
        {
            "text": "even or doubly even.", 
            "dur": "1.2", 
            "start": "188.03"
        }, 
        {
            "text": "So 12 would be doubly even\nbecause you can divide by 2", 
            "dur": "4.19", 
            "start": "189.23"
        }, 
        {
            "text": "and then 2 again.", 
            "dur": "1.39", 
            "start": "193.42"
        }, 
        {
            "text": "Well, by that sense, 0 can be\ndivided by 2 and 2 and 2 and", 
            "dur": "4.33", 
            "start": "194.81"
        }, 
        {
            "text": "2-- it is the most\neven number.", 
            "dur": "2.71", 
            "start": "199.14"
        }, 
        {
            "text": "The correct definition of\nan even number is it&#39;s", 
            "dur": "3.56", 
            "start": "201.85"
        }, 
        {
            "text": "a multiple of 2.", 
            "dur": "1.97", 
            "start": "205.41"
        }, 
        {
            "text": "Something times 2.", 
            "dur": "1.75", 
            "start": "207.38"
        }, 
        {
            "text": "Something times 2.", 
            "dur": "1.2", 
            "start": "209.13"
        }, 
        {
            "text": "Well, it is.", 
            "dur": "0.91", 
            "start": "210.33"
        }, 
        {
            "text": "There&#39;s no problem with that.", 
            "dur": "0.84", 
            "start": "211.24"
        }, 
        {
            "text": "It&#39;s 0 times 2.", 
            "dur": "1.72", 
            "start": "212.08"
        }, 
        {
            "text": "Great.", 
            "dur": "1.52", 
            "start": "213.8"
        }, 
        {
            "text": "Brady said it had to\nbe divisible by 2.", 
            "dur": "2.28", 
            "start": "215.32"
        }, 
        {
            "text": "Well, that works.", 
            "dur": "1.96", 
            "start": "217.6"
        }, 
        {
            "text": "0 divide by 2 is 0.", 
            "dur": "3.23", 
            "start": "219.56"
        }, 
        {
            "text": "OK, so it fits between\ntwo odd numbers.", 
            "dur": "2.235", 
            "start": "222.79"
        }, 
        {
            "text": "That might be a definition\nfor even.", 
            "dur": "1.905", 
            "start": "225.025"
        }, 
        {
            "text": "Let&#39;s do that.", 
            "dur": "1.17", 
            "start": "226.93"
        }, 
        {
            "text": "There&#39;s 0.", 
            "dur": "1.045", 
            "start": "228.1"
        }, 
        {
            "text": "And over here that&#39;s 1.", 
            "dur": "1.71", 
            "start": "229.145"
        }, 
        {
            "text": "Over here that&#39;s minus 1.", 
            "dur": "1.905", 
            "start": "230.855"
        }, 
        {
            "text": "And then you get 2 over\nhere, minus 2.", 
            "dur": "2.382", 
            "start": "232.76"
        }, 
        {
            "text": "Perfectly fits.", 
            "dur": "1.523", 
            "start": "235.142"
        }, 
        {
            "text": "There are some rules\nfor numbers.", 
            "dur": "1.645", 
            "start": "236.665"
        }, 
        {
            "text": "Some arithmetic rules.", 
            "dur": "1.32", 
            "start": "238.31"
        }, 
        {
            "text": "Two even numbers, if you add two\neven numbers together, you", 
            "dur": "3.54", 
            "start": "239.63"
        }, 
        {
            "text": "get an even number.", 
            "dur": "1.44", 
            "start": "243.17"
        }, 
        {
            "text": "Well, that works.", 
            "dur": "1.66", 
            "start": "244.61"
        }, 
        {
            "text": "0 plus 4 is 4, an even\nnumber again.", 
            "dur": "3.21", 
            "start": "246.27"
        }, 
        {
            "text": "That&#39;s what we want.", 
            "dur": "0.94", 
            "start": "249.48"
        }, 
        {
            "text": "We&#39;re saying 0 is even.", 
            "dur": "1.5", 
            "start": "250.42"
        }, 
        {
            "text": "It follows every definition.", 
            "dur": "2.55", 
            "start": "251.92"
        }, 
        {
            "text": "In fact, if it wasn&#39;t even, then\nit would break our rules", 
            "dur": "5.07", 
            "start": "254.47"
        }, 
        {
            "text": "of arithmetic, which would\nbe a disaster.", 
            "dur": "2.98", 
            "start": "259.54"
        }, 
        {
            "text": "It is true to say that 0 is\nneither positive or negative.", 
            "dur": "4.69", 
            "start": "262.52"
        }, 
        {
            "text": "It sits here between the\npositive numbers and the", 
            "dur": "3.51", 
            "start": "267.21"
        }, 
        {
            "text": "negative numbers.", 
            "dur": "1.115", 
            "start": "270.72"
        }, 
        {
            "text": "So it is neither positive\nor negative.", 
            "dur": "3.095", 
            "start": "271.835"
        }, 
        {
            "text": "ROGER BOWLEY: The discovery of\n0 was the most important", 
            "dur": "2.96", 
            "start": "274.93"
        }, 
        {
            "text": "advance in mathematics of all,\nbecause it made mathematics", 
            "dur": "3.54", 
            "start": "277.89"
        }, 
        {
            "text": "capable of being understood\nby everybody.", 
            "dur": "2.04", 
            "start": "281.43"
        }, 
        {
            "text": "Everybody could do\nthis mathematics.", 
            "dur": "1.84", 
            "start": "283.47"
        }, 
        {
            "text": "JAMES GRIME: The Babylonians,\nthe Greeks, they had the idea", 
            "dur": "2.26", 
            "start": "285.31"
        }, 
        {
            "text": "of a space.", 
            "dur": "1.46", 
            "start": "287.57"
        }, 
        {
            "text": "So there was a difference\nbetween 26, 2", 
            "dur": "2.53", 
            "start": "289.03"
        }, 
        {
            "text": "and 6, and 206, 2-0-6.", 
            "dur": "4.07", 
            "start": "291.56"
        }, 
        {
            "text": "They had a space there.", 
            "dur": "1", 
            "start": "295.63"
        }, 
        {
            "text": "They didn&#39;t use the symbol\n0, but they had a space.", 
            "dur": "2.71", 
            "start": "296.63"
        }, 
        {
            "text": "It was more like a\npunctuation mark.", 
            "dur": "2.44", 
            "start": "299.34"
        }, 
        {
            "text": "So the Babylonians would\nunderstand the difference", 
            "dur": "2.32", 
            "start": "301.78"
        }, 
        {
            "text": "between 26 and 206.", 
            "dur": "5.71", 
            "start": "304.1"
        }, 
        {
            "text": "But instead of using the symbol\nfor 0, they would just", 
            "dur": "3.03", 
            "start": "309.81"
        }, 
        {
            "text": "have a space.", 
            "dur": "1.64", 
            "start": "312.84"
        }, 
        {
            "text": "However, if they wanted\nto write 260, 260 was", 
            "dur": "4.566", 
            "start": "314.48"
        }, 
        {
            "text": "written like this.", 
            "dur": "0.934", 
            "start": "319.046"
        }, 
        {
            "text": "And to us, that looks like 26.", 
            "dur": "3.05", 
            "start": "319.98"
        }, 
        {
            "text": "To them and in context,\nthat would make sense.", 
            "dur": "2.78", 
            "start": "323.03"
        }, 
        {
            "text": "But they didn&#39;t have this\nidea of 0 by itself.", 
            "dur": "3.83", 
            "start": "325.81"
        }, 
        {
            "text": "In the 9th century, the\nfirst instance--", 
            "dur": "3.36", 
            "start": "329.64"
        }, 
        {
            "text": "or the first recorded\ninstance of 0--", 
            "dur": "3.11", 
            "start": "333"
        }, 
        {
            "text": "was found.", 
            "dur": "0.65", 
            "start": "336.11"
        }, 
        {
            "text": "It was actually found by a\ngardener keeping track of the", 
            "dur": "3.42", 
            "start": "336.76"
        }, 
        {
            "text": "number of flowers that his\ngarden would produce.", 
            "dur": "2.43", 
            "start": "340.18"
        }, 
        {
            "text": "And he used the number 50 as\nwe would recognize it.", 
            "dur": "2.89", 
            "start": "342.61"
        }, 
        {
            "text": "5, 0.", 
            "dur": "1.96", 
            "start": "345.5"
        }, 
        {
            "text": "After that point, they started\nto experiment with 0.", 
            "dur": "3.13", 
            "start": "347.46"
        }, 
        {
            "text": "What could it do?", 
            "dur": "2.09", 
            "start": "350.59"
        }, 
        {
            "text": "If you add 0, it makes\nno difference.", 
            "dur": "2.54", 
            "start": "352.68"
        }, 
        {
            "text": "If you times by 0, you get 0.", 
            "dur": "3.45", 
            "start": "355.22"
        }, 
        {
            "text": "Dividing by 0--", 
            "dur": "2.18", 
            "start": "358.67"
        }, 
        {
            "text": "that caused them some problems\nas it still does today.", 
            "dur": "3.11", 
            "start": "360.85"
        }, 
        {
            "text": "ROGER BOWLEY: In this sense,\nthe mathematical sense, the", 
            "dur": "2.12", 
            "start": "363.96"
        }, 
        {
            "text": "number 0 does not\nmean nothing.", 
            "dur": "2.81", 
            "start": "366.08"
        }, 
        {
            "text": "It means a quantity which you\ncan manipulate in the", 
            "dur": "2.94", 
            "start": "368.89"
        }, 
        {
            "text": "mathematics.", 
            "dur": "0.76", 
            "start": "371.83"
        }, 
        {
            "text": "And so it&#39;s better to call\nit 0 rather than nothing.", 
            "dur": "3.72", 
            "start": "372.59"
        }, 
        {
            "text": "Nothing is when you&#39;re\ncounting.", 
            "dur": "1.74", 
            "start": "376.31"
        }, 
        {
            "text": "There&#39;s nothing there.", 
            "dur": "1.29", 
            "start": "378.05"
        }, 
        {
            "text": "0 is the abstract mathematical\nquantity.", 
            "dur": "3.19", 
            "start": "379.34"
        }, 
        {
            "text": "CGP GREY: I&#39;m CGP Grey and\nmy favorite number is 0.", 
            "dur": "3.45", 
            "start": "382.53"
        }, 
        {
            "text": "I like 0 because it&#39;s not\nan obvious number.", 
            "dur": "3.85", 
            "start": "385.98"
        }, 
        {
            "text": "You can have counting systems\nwhere there&#39;s one thing, two", 
            "dur": "2.91", 
            "start": "389.83"
        }, 
        {
            "text": "things, three things,\nfour things.", 
            "dur": "1.94", 
            "start": "392.74"
        }, 
        {
            "text": "But mathematics existed for a\nlong time without having a 0", 
            "dur": "3.88", 
            "start": "394.68"
        }, 
        {
            "text": "as part of it.", 
            "dur": "0.65", 
            "start": "398.56"
        }, 
        {
            "text": "So it&#39;s a number, but\nit also isn&#39;t", 
            "dur": "3.01", 
            "start": "399.21"
        }, 
        {
            "text": "anything in and of itself.", 
            "dur": "1.46", 
            "start": "402.22"
        }
    ], 
